# Project 4. Dos cuadrados, pero más fáciles 

Again the idea is to draw more squares, as in the previous activity.
And again we will propose you with two challenges.
But in this opportunity, you need to find how to define your _own_ commands; 
in the project code there is some help.

A) The challenge here is, again to draw 2 squares with sides of 3 stones of length.
But now you need to find out how to complete the parts that are already there, and how to use them.
The final board is exactly the same as in the first challenge of the previous project.
After finishing this one, remember there is a second challeng.

> **More vocabulary**
>
> The **main program** is the part of the code that the machines looks for in order to start the execution.
> A complete program is always made by several procedures (zero or more) and one main program.

&nbsp;

> **To remember**
>
> A command is the _description_ of an _action_.
> It may be a built-in command, or one defined by means of a **procedure**. 
> And because commands describe actions, when we define a new command, the chosen name must start with a verb,
> just as the names of built-in commands: draw, drop, move, etc.

B) After you saved your solution, change the program so it draws _four_ squares, as it is shown in the following image.
   The most complex part is to position the head in each case in the cell where the drawing should begin… 
   However, you already have your own command to draw a square!

<center>
![Final board expected after challenge 2](data:image/png;base64,)
</center>

> **Reusing is the key**
>
> To reuse is to take advantage of a program or procedure that was already built, so you do not need to do it again,
> and only perform small adjustments to it in order to solve the new problem.
